snippet.textDisplay:
Bellew - 'Wilder isn't technically good enough to line Tyson Fury up for that big punch'... That's clearly not true because he did exactly that in their first fight? Totally lines Fury up as Fury tries to duck it and nails him with a right hand-left hook. And of course, Fury by some miracle gets up, amazing, massive credit to Fury, one of the greatest boxing moments ever - the character of it is inspiring. But the simple truth is, that one-two combo ends 99/100 fights. It could feasibly end Wilder-Fury III because not even Tyson Fury could take that shot again and get up again. Had Fury not got up in time, there never would have been a Wilder-Fury II and all the hype would be about a Joshua-Wilder unification.

The worst thing Fury could do now is write Wilder off as some underweight, sloppy bum of a fighter and a stepping stone to the Joshua fight. He isn't a bum. He's a genuine champion who got (totally) outboxed in 1 of his 44 fights, which is a pretty damn good record. Wilder doesn't have technique but most days he doesn't need it. He's a natural one punch finisher, arguably the best there's ever been. The guy can lose all 12 rounds but win any match with 1 punch. Yes he's one-dimensional but he's a seriously dangerous fighter, a fighter who can end your career. You simply cannot disrespect a guy who's knocked out 41 of his 44 opponents, 42 if you include the Fury knockdown, held a major heavyweight title for 5 years etc... Fury may be a better technical boxer and nearing his top physical condition now, fine, but none of that matters if you just happen to take that 1 Wilder punch. People forget that Wilder had Fury on the brink of retirement in their first fight - winning and losing is about fine margins.

Despite the British media hype, the Fury-Joshua unification at Wembley Stadium is effectively 2 fights away. For now it's nothing but a fairytale fight which is why it shouldn't even come into the mindset of either Fury or Joshua. Respect and prepare for the guy who wants to knock you out right now - Wilder and Pulev.
